[3] Diarrhea, amoebic dysentery - Saudi Arabia (Makkah Province)
Date: Wed 9 Feb 2011
Source: Arab News [edited]
<http://arabnews.com/saudiarabia/article254573.ece>


A number of people have been treated for dysentery following the 26
Jan 2011 floods in Jeddah, although the exact numbers are unknown.
Pharmacies have also reported a rise in the number of people asking
for diarrhea medication.

According to Sami Badawood, the city's director of health affairs, 161
people were admitted to hospital following the floods for a variety of
reasons. However, complaints include not only dysentery, but also
panic and asthma attacks triggered by the floods.

A case of dysentery serious enough to require hospitalization was that
of a 45-year-old Filipino who was rushed to hospital on Sunday
evening, 6 Feb 2011, suffering from acute amoebic dysentery. He fell
ill after consuming tap water that turned out to have been
contaminated when the sewage-filled floodwaters entered the
underground water tank where he lives.

The man's boss, who is manager of a major Jeddah interior decoration
company, said that a quarter of his workforce had come down with
dysentery, although not all at the same time. He added that this man
was the worst case.

This illness is a warning to other Jeddah residents not to drink tap
water. On Sat 5 Feb 2011, they were advised by Badawood not to do so.
He said that 70 percent of water in storage tanks had been
contaminated by the floods and people should drink only bottled water
until further notice. On Sun 6 Feb 2011, city doctors warned that the
symptoms of diseases caught from contaminated water might not manifest
for several months.

[Byline: Rima Al-Mukhtar]

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is likely that the outbreak of diarrheal illness in Jeddah is of
polymicrobial origin given the contamination of the drinking water
with sewage. - Mod.LL]

